top.value: A Compact Program may be suspended or terminated, among other conditions, if the country (i) fails to comply with its commitments under the agreements entered into with MCC in relation to the program, (ii) engages in a pattern of actions inconsistent with the criteria used by MCC to determine eligibility for the program, or (iii) engages in activities contrary to the national security interests of the United States. Disbursements of funding under a Compact Program are subject to specific conditions set forth in the Compact Program agreement for the individual projects funded thereby, as well as general conditions, such as the delivery of implementation, fiscal accountability, and monitoring and evaluation plans.

10.3. there has been progress satisfactory to MCC on the M&E Plan and Social and Gender Integration Plan for the Program, relevant Project or Activity and substantial compliance with the requirements of the M&E Plan and Social and Gender Integration Plan (including the targets set forth therein and any applicable reporting requirements set forth therein for the relevant Disbursement Period)

10) Any Taxes paid with MCC Funding through the date ninety (90) days prior to the start of the applicable Disbursement Period have been reimbursed by the Government in full in accordance with the Compact.

Due diligence funding is used to obtain sufficient information to evaluate, assess and appraise projects during compact development, effectively oversee and monitor compact implementation, conduct quality assurance, and then evaluate the results of a compact project once complete.

609(g) funding is used pre-compact for key project preparation work such as feasibility and environmental impact studies, engineering designs, baseline surveys, financial management and procurement technical assistance, and other specialized analysis to help MCC determine the final suitability and scope of investments, costs, implementation risks, and mitigation measures.

The goal of PEPFAR funding is to initiate a data revolution to achieve greater transparency, mutual accountability and local impact in Sub-Saharan Africa.  The program will seek to attempt to address some of the root causes of insufficient data use for decision-making around HIV/AIDS, broader health, gender equality, and economic growth.

MCC is authorized under section 614(g) of its legislation to contract with any nongovernmental organization (including a university, independent foundation, or other organization) in the United States or in a candidate country that is undertaking research aimed at improving data related to eligibility criteria with respect to the country.
